 build networks among themselves and effect change within UN processes. Using a multidimensional understanding of state sovereignty, the authors find that states use sovereignty to shelter not only material interests but also cultural identity in the face of external pressure. This book is unique in its analysis of NGO activities at the international level as well as the complexity of nation-states' responses to their new companions in global governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil society. 0aEnvironmental economics. 0aHuman rights. 0aNon-governmental organizations. 0aSovereignty. 0aWomen's rights. 0aWorld politicsy1989-. 4aPolitics and Law : Comparative Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aClark, Ann Marie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHochstetler, Kathryn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aN. Rosenau, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791483848423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791483848/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles